from necrotic cardiac myocytes, are independently predictive of morbidity and mortality among patients with UA (discussed later). According to the European Society of Cardiology/American College of Cardiology (ESC/ACC), troponin elevations in this clinical setting are, by definition, NSTEMI. 4. Clinical risk classification systems. Numerous scores have been derived to facilitate risk assessment and guide medical therapy in patients with NSTE-ACS. It is important to note that these scores can also be used to determine which patients may benefit most from early invasive therapy as opposed to a more conservative approach. The Braunwald classification system risk-stratifies patients with UA at presentation (Table 2.2). Braunwald defined UA according to the characteristics of anginal pain and the underlying cause. Patients with
